	INSERT INTO [dbo].[SkillsModuleVideos](SMVideoId,[Title],[Text],[F4V],[MP4],[OGV],[Type],[TextPosition])VALUES(@SMVideoID,'Temperature - Rectal','<p><b>Rectal Temperature</b></p><p>You might not need to take a client''s rectal temperature very often. But it is a useful method to evaluate a client''s core temperature, and is considered the most accurate way to measure body temperature.</p>','Temperature_Rectal.f4v ','Temperature_Rectal.mp4','Temperature_Rectal.ogv',2,0)
	SET IDENTITY_INSERT SkillsModuleVideos OFF
	INSERT INTO [dbo].[SMVideoMapping]([TestId],[SMVideoId],[OrderNumber]) VALUES (@TestId,@SMVideoID,9)

	Set @SMVideoID = @SMVideoID + 1 --36
	SET IDENTITY_INSERT SkillsModuleVideos ON
	INSERT INTO [dbo].[SkillsModuleVideos](SMVideoId,[Title],[Text],[F4V],[MP4],[OGV],[Type],[TextPosition])VALUES(@SMVideoID,'Temperature - Rectal','<p>Taking a rectal temperature is a simple matter. After washing hands and gloving (ask if the client has a latex allergy), you lubricate the rectal thermometer tip with ointment. Then gently insert it into the anal sphincter about 1/2 inch. Hold it in place until it registers a final number. That''s all there is to it!</p><p>Clean the equipment following manufacturer''s directions. Record the result followed by an "R," to indicate that the temperature was taken rectally. Remember to expect the client''s rectal temperature to be at least one degree higher (normal of 99.6°F) than their oral temperature.</p>','','','',1,0)
	SET IDENTITY_INSERT SkillsModuleVideos OFF
	INSERT INTO [dbo].[SMVideoMapping]([TestId],[SMVideoId],[OrderNumber]) VALUES (@TestId,@SMVideoID,10)
	
	Set @SMVideoID = @SMVideoID + 1 --37
	SET IDENTITY_INSERT SkillsModuleVideos ON
	INSERT INTO [dbo].[SkillsModuleVideos](SMVideoId,[Title],[Text],[F4V],[MP4],[OGV],[Type],[TextPosition])VALUES(@SMVideoID,'Temperature - Axillary','<p><b>Axillary Temperature</b></p><p>To take on axillary temperature, you use the same electronic temperature probe as you would use to take an oral temperature. You just place it in the client''s armpit, rather than in their mouth. What could be simpler?</p>','Temperature_Axillary.f4v','Temperature_Axillary.mp4','Temperature_Axillary.ogv',2,0)
	SET IDENTITY_INSERT SkillsModuleVideos OFF
	INSERT INTO [dbo].[SMVideoMapping]([TestId],[SMVideoId],[OrderNumber]) VALUES (@TestId,@SMVideoID,11)
	
	Set @SMVideoID = @SMVideoID + 1 --38
	SET IDENTITY_INSERT SkillsModuleVideos ON
	INSERT INTO [dbo].[SkillsModuleVideos](SMVideoId,[Title],[Text],[F4V],[MP4],[OGV],[Type],[TextPosition])VALUES(@SMVideoID,'Temperature - Axillary','<p>Many steps of taking an axillary temperature are going to sound familiar:</p><p><ul><li>Wash your hands</li><li>Examine the probe for cracks or other damage</li><li>Put the probe cover on the thermometer</li><li>Ask the client to raise one arm</li><li>Since you need to have the thermometer surrounded by dry skin, adjust clothing or absorb moisture as needed</li><li>Position the probe high in the client''s armpit</li><li>Have client press their arm against their torso, to hold the thermometer in place</li><li>Wait for the probe''s visual or sound signal of completion</li><li>Withdraw the probe, and read the client''s temperature</li><li>Discard the probe cover into a biohazard container</li><li>Document the client''s temperature folowed by an "AX," to indicate that it was an axiary reading</li></ul></p><p>Note the similarities of taking an oral, tympanic, and axillary temperatures. Remember to expect the client''s axillary temperature to be one degree lower (normal of 97.6°F) than their oral temperature.</p>','','','',1,0)
	SET IDENTITY_INSERT SkillsModuleVideos OFF
